entry.title: Karabakh mother mourns the death of her two children

media:group.media:title: Karabakh mother mourns the death of her two children
media:group.media:description:
Vera Narimanyan lost her two children last week. The single mother of three-year-old Leo and six-year-old Gita, who lives in Aghabekalanj Village in Karabakhโs Martakert region, left her sleeping children alone at home to walk 5 kilometers to the nearby town of Martakert to get cooking oil, sugar, and other foods.
Azerbaijanโs blockade of the region has caused critical supply shortages of essential foods and other household items. The lack of fuel means that a small amount of local production is unable to reach remote areas like Aghabekalanj. Deciding to spare her two children from the heat, she left them sleeping at home. After waking up, the children left their home to look for their mother, eventually reaching Martakert. The next day their lifeless bodies were discovered in a car parked on a street in Martakert. According to preliminary data, the children had gotten into the car, fallen asleep, and died from heat exhaustion.

entry.title: Hanna Notte: The Russia-Turkey-Middle East Nexus

media:group.media:title: Hanna Notte: The Russia-Turkey-Middle East Nexus
media:group.media:description:
Hanna Notte, an expert on Russian foreign and security policy, gave a lecture on Russia-Turkey relations and their repercussions for the South Caucasus and Middle East.
Hanna Notte is a Senior Research Associate at the Vienna Center for Disarmament and Non-Proliferation and a Senior Associate (non-resident) in the Europe, Russia, and Eurasia Program at the Center for Strategic & International Studies in Washington, D.C.
The lecture was given at an international symposium on Russia organized by the Middlebury Institute of International Studies at Monterey in Yerevan and Tsaghkadzor, Armenia on July 2-12, 2023.
